A subbase for a topology on a set X is a subset \mathcal {S} of its power set. The base generated by \mathcal {S} is the set of all finite intersections of elements of S. The topology generated by \mathcal {S} is any of the following equivalent sets:
the topology generated by this base;
the coarsest topology containing \mathcal {S};
the closure of \mathcal {S} under finite intersections and then arbitrary unions.

Since universal elements are initial, the colimit
  D\xrightarrow {\lambda } \operatorname *{colim} D of a diagram J\xrightarrow {D} C is
  initial in the category of elements \text {el}(\operatorname *{Cocone}_D),
  in the sense that for any other cocone
  D\xrightarrow {\mu } c, there exists a unique map \operatorname *{lim} D\to  c so that each of
  the following triangles commute:




